</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586196B3FFEC388FAFE05FB78" blockId="11.[232,1215,1073,1758]" pageId="11" pageNumber="74">Geographic distribution. From 'Rangari' south to Glenbawn.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586196B3FFEC2889FFBA2FA89" blockId="11.[232,1215,1073,1758]" box="[282,1080,1259,1298]" pageId="11" pageNumber="74">Geological age. Middle to late Tournaisian.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BFD36D586196B3FFEC1896DFD55F945" blockId="11.[232,1215,1073,1758]" pageId="11" pageNumber="74">
Remarks. This is a very common species of relatively large size. The single specimen (FI773, Geological and Mining Museum, Sydney) described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD34B2486196B3FFC6C8901FEC2FA50" author="Dun, W. S. &amp; W. N. Benson" pageId="11" pageNumber="74" pagination="337 - 374" refId="ref24926" refString="Dun, W. S. &amp; W. N. Benson, 1920. The Geology and Petrology of the Great Serpentine Belt of New South Wales, Pt IX. Section B. Palaeontology. Linnean Society of New South Wales Proceedings 45 (3): 337 - 374, pis 18 - 24." type="journal article" year="1920">
<collectingRegion id="4986F83786196B3FFC6C8901FC66FA06" box="[948,1020,1397,1437]" country="United Kingdom" name="Down" pageId="11" pageNumber="74">Dun</collectingRegion>
&amp; Benson (1920)
</bibRefCitation>
from Carroll is missing (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD34B2486196B3FFC8E89D0FED9FA62" author="Campbell, K. S. W. &amp; B. Engel" pageId="11" pageNumber="74" pagination="55 - 122" refId="ref24605" refString="Campbell, K. S. W. &amp; B. Engel, 1963. The Faunas of the Tournaisian Tulcumba Sandstone and its Members in the Werrie and Belvue Synclines, N. S. W. Geological Society of Australia Journal 10 (1): 55 - 122." type="journal article" year="1963">Campbell &amp; Engel, 1963</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen here chosen as 
<typeStatus id="54F9887786196B3FFC5B89A6FB86FA62" box="[899,1052,1490,1529]" pageId="11" pageNumber="74">lectotype</typeStatus>
is rather young and well preserved. It was recovered from the lower part of the Namoi Formation in Swains Gully, where the species occurs abundantly (Locality 25). The species has a short and smooth protoconch, and is planispiral in early whorls.
</paragraph>
